Here's a PlantUML sequence diagram representing the control flow for the Books Store application based on the provided information:

```plantuml
@startuml vishipayyallore_blazorwasm-apim-api-sql-redis

actor User
participant "Blazor WebAssembly\nUI" as UI
participant "API Management" as APIM
participant "ASP.NET Core API" as API
participant "Business Logic Layer" as BLL
participant "Cache Repository" as Cache
participant "SQL Repository" as SQL

User -> UI: Requests book data
UI -> APIM: HTTP GET /api/books
APIM -> API: Forwards request
API -> BLL: GetBooks()
BLL -> Cache: TryGetBooks()

alt Books in cache
    Cache --> BLL: Return cached books
else Books not in cache
    BLL -> SQL: GetBooks()
    SQL --> BLL: Return books from database
    BLL -> Cache: StoreBooks()
end

BLL --> API: Return books
API --> APIM: HTTP 200 OK with books
APIM --> UI: Returns books data
UI --> User: Displays books

User -> UI: Add/Edit/Delete book
UI -> APIM: HTTP POST/PUT/DELETE /api/books
APIM -> API: Forwards request
API -> BLL: ProcessBookOperation()
BLL -> SQL: ExecuteDatabaseOperation()
SQL --> BLL: Confirm operation
BLL -> Cache: InvalidateCache()
BLL --> API: Operation result
API --> APIM: HTTP 200 OK
APIM --> UI: Confirms operation
UI --> User: Updates display

@enduml
```

This sequence diagram illustrates the control flow for both reading book data and performing write operations (add/edit/delete) in the Books Store application. It shows the interaction between the user, Blazor WebAssembly UI, API Management, ASP.NET Core API, Business Logic Layer, Cache Repository, and SQL Repository.